      "astronomy_myth": "Astronomically, the sixth house corresponds to the sector of the zodiac traditionally associated with Virgo, a constellation linked to the harvest and purification. In mythology, this house connects to figures of service, healing, and meticulous craft. The Greek goddess Hygieia (personification of health) and the centaur Chiron (the wounded healer) are archetypal figures here, representing the integration of physical care and spiritual wisdom. Mesopotamian traditions viewed this sector as the \"House of Health and Servitude,\" where celestial influences governed daily labor and bodily well-being. This house symbolizes the cosmic principle of order emerging from chaos through diligent work—mirroring the myth of Demeter separating grain from chaff, or Asclepius refining healing arts through systematic practice. It reflects humanity's eternal struggle to impose meaningful structure on the mundane aspects of existence.",
      "psychology": "From a Jungian perspective, House 6 represents the **development of the ego's adaptive functions** through engagement with daily reality. This is where the psyche learns discrimination (Virgo) and communicative integration (Mercury) by structuring the unconscious flow of House 12 into conscious routines. The sixth house governs what Jung called the \"personal unconscious\" territory related to bodily instincts and work habits—where shadow material often manifests as psychosomatic symptoms or compulsive behaviors. It's the arena for **individuation through service**, where one confronts the tension between perfectionist control (Virgo shadow) and holistic acceptance. The house activates the **inferior function** (often sensation for intuitive types) by demanding practical engagement with physical reality. Successful navigation requires balancing Mercury's analytical mind with Virgo's earthy pragmatism, transforming neurotic self-criticism into constructive self-improvement. This house ultimately teaches that spiritual wholeness requires honoring the temple of the body and finding sacredness in humble acts.",
